comment.body:
This is the risk I listed as the LOCAL_CONSISTENCY_TODO with the comment. The risk to hit it is
1. massive records fails at the exact the operationTime on the same partition, number is more than the page size.
2. None of them can be fixed by the repair thread.

RepairRequests is not a generic database. It's used to fix the requests and the record will be removed as long as it's fixed. If we hit this condition, that means there are massive records somehow we couldn't fix for this partition. It's already a red flag. We have a metrics for it and will set SLA0 to SLA2 alert for that.

The table is indexed by operationTime because we handle the error in order. If we want to totally solve the problem, we need a combined index of operationTime with BlobId.

[vcr-2.0] Use azure-sdk-bom to manage azure libs (#2632)

Issue: Azure/azure-sdk-for-java#37223
Ref: https://devblogs.microsoft.com/azure-sdk/dependency-management-for-java/

MSFT recommends using azure-sdk-bom to manage azure dependencies instead of us pulling in specific versions. Azure SDK BOM automatically pulls in right versions, so we don't have to specify them.

[vcr-2.0] Remove redundant metadata (#2627)

We identify permanent blobs in two different ways.

A lack of expiration-time means the blob is permanent
expiration = -1 also means the blob is permanent
Similarly, in case of deletion

A lack of deletion-time means the blob must not be purged from cloud.
A deletion-time = -1 also means the blob must not be purged from cloud.
This distinction is not useful anywhere and not used at all during compaction or recovery.
It would be clearer if we just remove the deletion-time field from metadata to indicate the blob must not be purged, and remove expiration-time to indicate blob is permanent.
add dry-run config and check other configs

pull_request.title: [vcr-2.0] Remove redundant metadata
pull_request.body:
We identify permanent blobs in two different ways.

1. A lack of expiration-time means the blob is permanent
2. expiration = -1 also means the blob is permanent

Similarly, in case of deletion
1. A lack of deletion-time means the blob  must not be purged from cloud. 
2. A deletion-time = -1 also means the blob must not be purged from cloud.

This distinction is not useful anywhere and not used at all during compaction or recovery.
It would be clearer if we just remove the deletion-time field from metadata to indicate the blob must not be purged, and remove expiration-time to indicate blob is permanent.

comment.body:
Its not required for all records to have the same operation time. If greater than "pageSize" records have the same operation time, then token will not advance.
Can we make something more unique as a token? Maybe a combination of `blobId` and `operationType`?
